</ul></nav><button id="responsive-menu" role="button" aria-controls="genesis-nav-primary" aria-pressed="false"><span class="screen-reader-text">Menu</span></button></div></header><div class="site-inner"><div class="wrap"><div class="content-sidebar-wrap"><main class="content" id="genesis-content"><article class="post-25399 post type-post status-publish format-standard has-post-thumbnail category-security-education category-website-security tag-black-hat-tactics tag-phishing tag-redirects-2 entry"><header class="entry-header"><div class="single-featured"><img width="745" height="350" src="https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/05202020_SteamPhishing_blog-745x350.png" class="single-featured-image wp-post-image" alt="Steam Phishing" loading="lazy" srcset="https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/05202020_SteamPhishing_blog.png 745w, https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/05202020_SteamPhishing_blog-600x282.png 600w, https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/05202020_SteamPhishing_blog-650x305.png 650w, https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/05202020_SteamPhishing_blog-585x275.png 585w, https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/05202020_SteamPhishing_blog-560x263.png 560w" sizes="(max-width: 745px) 100vw, 745px" /></div><h1 class="entry-title">Steam Phishing Campaign Uses CS:GO Skin Gambling Lure</h1>
<p class="entry-meta"><time class="entry-time" datetime="2020-05-20T12:11:02-07:00">May 20, 2020</time><span class="entry-author"><a href="https://blog.sucuri.net/author/luke" class="entry-author-link" rel="author"><span class="entry-author-name">Luke Leal</span></a></span></p></header><div class="entry-content"><aside class="mashsb-container mashsb-main mashsb-stretched"><div class="mashsb-box"><div class="mashsb-buttons"><a class="mashicon-facebook mash-small mash-center mashsb-shadow" href="https://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Fblog.sucuri.net%2F2020%2F05%2Fsteam-phishing-csgo-skin-gambling-lure.html" target="_top" rel="nofollow"><span class="icon"></span><span class="text">Facebook</span></a><a class="mashicon-twitter mash-small mash-center mashsb-shadow" href="https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?text=Steam%20Phishing%20Campaign%20Uses%20CS%3AGO%20Skin%20Gambling%20Lure&url=https://blog.sucuri.net/2020/05/steam-phishing-csgo-skin-gambling-lure.html&via=sucurisecurity" target="_top" rel="nofollow"><span class="icon"></span><span class="text">Twitter</span></a><a class="mashicon-subscribe mash-small mash-center mashsb-shadow" href="#" target="_top" rel="nofollow"><span class="icon"></span><span class="text">Subscribe</span></a><div class="onoffswitch2 mash-small mashsb-shadow" style="display:none;"></div></div>
            </div>
                <div style="clear:both;"></div></aside>
            <!-- Share buttons by mashshare.net - Version: 3.8.1--><p>Attackers regularly target online gaming accounts as they can quickly sell any transferable items along with account logins to a third party. This scenario has cropped up for years now, and has affected a growing number of popular online games ranging from Runescape to Fortnite.</p>
<p>These games run on their own clients — so stealing logins will only give the attacker access to that specific game (sometimes a few others). To gain broader access, attackers are choosing to target digital distribution clients like Steam or Origin. These clients allow multiple games to be managed under a single account, and include popular games like <i>Counter-Strike: Global Offensive</i> (<i>CSGO</i>) which boast tens of millions of players.</p>
<p>A large player base means there will be a higher demand for the accounts and any associated items — ultimately making it more attractive to bad actors, since they won’t have to wait long for interested buyers. The longer the attacker has to “sit” on the stolen account, the higher the chance of the owner being able to regain access and prevent the attacker from using it.</p>
<figure id="attachment_25400" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-25400" style="width: 467px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_GSGO.png"><img loading="lazy" class="wp-image-25400 size-large" src="https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_GSGO-467x650.png" alt="Active Listing for Phished Prime Account" width="467" height="650" srcset="https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_GSGO-467x650.png 467w, https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_GSGO-432x600.png 432w, https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_GSGO-768x1068.png 768w, https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_GSGO-560x779.png 560w, https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_GSGO.png 1040w" sizes="(max-width: 467px) 100vw, 467px" /></a><figcaption id="caption-attachment-25400" class="wp-caption-text">An active listing of a fresh CS:GO Prime account being sold online</figcaption></figure>
<h2>CS:GO Skin Gambling Phishing Lure</h2>
<p>This phishing page was initially reported to us through <a href="mailto:labs@sucuri.net" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">labs@sucuri.net</a>. Upon investigation, we found it had been set up under a recently registered (2020-03-10) domain <b>csgo500[.]org</b>.</p>
<p>Evidently, this domain had been intentionally selected to mimic the victim site <b>csgo500[.]com</b>, which offers users the ability to gamble in-game CS:GO items on their platform — a feature commonly referred to as <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skin_gambling" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">skin gambling</a>.</p>
<p>One interesting point to note is that the original domain being imitated by this phishing campaign (<b>csgo500[.]com</b>) has geoblocking enabled, and does not allow entry for requests from the United States. It also prevents access from the Netherlands, Curaçao, France, or any other country where online gambling is prohibited.</p>
<p>On the other hand, the phishing website <b>csgo500[.]org </b>doesn’t mimic this geoblocking and allows requests from these countries.</p>
<p>Before a user can gamble, they must first “fund” their account by transferring in-game items (skins) from their Steam account (or at least validate their existence). To accomplish this, the user needs to log into their Steam account. This is usually done by redirecting the user to the Steam website, the user authenticates as they normally would, and then it redirects them back to the original website.</p>
<p><figure id="attachment_25401" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-25401" style="width: 650px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_skin_gambling.png"><img loading="lazy" class="wp-image-25401 size-large" src="https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_skin_gambling-650x424.png" alt="User authentication" width="650" height="424" srcset="https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_skin_gambling-650x424.png 650w, https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_skin_gambling-600x391.png 600w, https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_skin_gambling-768x501.png 768w, https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_skin_gambling-1536x1001.png 1536w, https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_skin_gambling-560x365.png 560w, https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_skin_gambling.png 1600w" sizes="(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px" /></a><figcaption id="caption-attachment-25401" class="wp-caption-text">A “Wheel of Fortune” CS:GO skin gambling betting game on the csgo500[.]com</figcaption></figure>The phishing page on <b>csgo500[.]org </b>handles this authentication process in a different, more deceptive way.</p>
<h2>Phishing Behavior</h2>
<p>One of the primary red flags is the behavior of the phishing page found on the malicious  <b>csgo500[.]org</b> domain, which allows attackers to harvest user credentials from unsuspecting victims.</p>
<p>Whenever a user clicks the <b>Sign in</b> button, the phishing site spawns an iframe that spoofs a new Chrome browser to load the official Steam login page, as seen below.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-25402" src="https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_behavior.gif" alt="Steam phishing page workflow" width="800" height="644" /></p>
<p>Whenever a victim enters their Steam account username and password and submits the data via a <b>POST</b> request, the malicious <b>csgo500[.]org</b> domain intercepts the login information before sending it to the original Steam website.</p>
<h3>Credential Validation &amp; Authentication Checks</h3>
<p>If a valid Steam account username and password is entered on the fake sign in page, attackers perform a quick validation of the login credentials before finally redirecting the victim to the real <b>csgo500[.]com </b>website.</p>
<p>Unless you happen to be viewing these requests in a browser’s developer tools, it can be hard to detect this malicious behavior. But there are still some signs that help show it’s suspicious.</p>
<ol>
<li>It will try to show the new iframe as a Chrome window regardless of the browser used, so if you aren’t using Chrome, a Chrome window should not open on its own.</li>
<li>The iframe for the fake Chrome window doesn’t operate as a normal browser window would. You can’t click things like the address bar or the SSL bar.</li>
</ol>
<p>Here’s an example of the <b>POST</b> request the phishing page sent when I was testing it. You can see it is submitted to <b>csgo500[.]org/checkData </b>instead of directly to the Steam web server.</p>
<p><a href="https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_post.png"><img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter wp-image-25403 size-large" src="https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_post-650x402.png" alt="Phishing page post request" width="650" height="402" srcset="https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_post-650x402.png 650w, https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_post-600x371.png 600w, https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_post-768x475.png 768w, https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_post-1536x950.png 1536w, https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_post-560x347.png 560w, https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_post.png 1600w" sizes="(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px" /></a></p>
<p>This is not the correct way to authenticate with Steam. Post requests containing plaintext login data shouldn’t be sent to third parties — and the malicious domain has indeed been set up in such a way so it can phish any login information submitted by victims.</p>
<p>In contrast, the legitimate <b>csgo500[.]com </b>domain follows proper development practices and  redirects users to Steam’s website for authentication. When the <b>POST</b> request is submitted during login, it is sent to the proper Steam authentication server — and not a third party that can steal it.</p>
<figure id="attachment_25404" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-25404" style="width: 650px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_redirect.png"><img loading="lazy" class="wp-image-25404 size-large" src="https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_redirect-650x417.png" alt="Phishing redirect" width="650" height="417" srcset="https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_redirect-650x417.png 650w, https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_redirect-600x385.png 600w, https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_redirect-768x492.png 768w, https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_redirect-560x359.png 560w, https://blog.sucuri.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/steam_phishing_redirect.png 1401w" sizes="(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px" /></a><figcaption id="caption-attachment-25404" class="wp-caption-text">The redirect to the Steam login URL &#8211; woth no iframe trickery</figcaption></figure>
<h2>Conclusion</h2>
<p>A phishing campaign can be tough to detect. Whether you’re a visitor or website owner, bad actors have a lot of clever tricks up their sleeves. As we saw from this campaign, attackers can successfully imitate a domain, two websites, and a Google Chrome popup window.</p>
<p>This is especially concerning for website owners who might be fraudulently imitated. In an example like this, the malicious domain and its website are hosted elsewhere. To best detect if a malicious phishing website is imitating your brand, you’ll likely need to set up some type of <a href="https://www.riskiq.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">brand monitoring</a> system. This can help protect your site from being tarnished by imitation phishing campaigns.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<aside class="mashsb-container mashsb-main mashsb-stretched"><div class="mashsb-box"><div class="mashsb-buttons"><a class="mashicon-facebook mash-small mash-center mashsb-shadow" href="https://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Fblog.sucuri.net%2F2020%2F05%2Fsteam-phishing-csgo-skin-gambling-lure.html" target="_top" rel="nofollow"><span class="icon"></span><span class="text">Facebook</span></a><a class="mashicon-twitter mash-small mash-center mashsb-shadow" href="https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?text=Steam%20Phishing%20Campaign%20Uses%20CS%3AGO%20Skin%20Gambling%20Lure&url=https://blog.sucuri.net/2020/05/steam-phishing-csgo-skin-gambling-lure.html&via=sucurisecurity" target="_top" rel="nofollow"><span class="icon"></span><span class="text">Twitter</span></a><a class="mashicon-subscribe mash-small mash-center mashsb-shadow" href="#" target="_top" rel="nofollow"><span class="icon"></span><span class="text">Subscribe</span></a><div class="onoffswitch2 mash-small mashsb-shadow" style="display:none;"></div></div>
